Oakland Center for Holistic Counseling
John F. Kennedy (JFK) University

The Center for Holistic Counseling provides a safe setting where adults, children, adolescents and seniors can find inner strength and direction through affordable personal counseling. Our counselors are advanced MA Counseling Psychology graduate students working under the supervision of licensed, professional psychotherapists. Clients receive active support while exploring such issues as:

Life transitions
Family conflicts and parenting
Relationship problems
Trauma, grief and loneliness
Spiritual crises
Anxiety, stress and depression
Incest and sexual abuse
Chronic pain and illness
Sexuality (all sexual orientations welcome)
Low-fee therapy groups are also offered, focusing on women’s and men’s issues, intimacy, depression and creativity.

Sliding-scale fees are available for individual and family clients. Low-fee group rates are also available.

Referrals will be made to other agencies for individuals who are acutely suicidal, potentially violent, suffering from severe psychiatric illness, or actively abusing drugs or alcohol.

Staff
Advanced graduate students in the Counseling Psychology program at JFK University's College of Graduate and Professional Studies provide counseling. All counselors work under the supervision of licensed, professional psychotherapists. 

Counselor trainees receive traditional clinical training specializing in either a transpersonal or somatic perspective. Their training prepares them to assist people with exploring their life challenges and seeing how these challenges relate to their thoughts, emotions, body, spirit and environment. 

Appointments
Appointments are offered on weekdays, evenings and Saturdays. The center is unable to accommodate drop-ins, but you are welcome to come by to discuss the services offered. The center is wheelchair accessible.

Eligibility
Referrals will be made to other agencies for individuals who are acutely suicidal, potentially violent, suffering from severe psychiatric illness, or actively abusing drugs or alcohol.

Fees
Affordable, sliding scale fees are available for individual and family clients. Low fee groups are also available.

Name: Philip Long
Notes:
I've been painting since 1987 and sewing leather since 1991.  I am a member of the East Bay Art Collective since it's inception in 2000.  Every year we put on a Dia de Los Muertos show called The Collumbarium where a large group of East Bay artists build individual altars which are put together to create a large installation.  in 2006 I combined my painting style with my years of experience in leather to create a 3D leather sculpture. It debuted at the Oakland Museum of California. The following year I went 2D gradually moving toward the style I now refer to as the leather mosaic.  

In 2008 my father John Long was killed by pirates off the coast of southern Mexico while attempting to sail solo to Ireland at the age of 78.  I created a large 12 X 6 foot leather mosaic in his honor which was unveiled at the Oakland Museum of California in 2008 to wonderful and touching reviews.  It is my goal to get this piece into The Crawford Art Gallery in Cork, Ireland.  That is where dad was going on his journey and I'd like to help him finish his trip.  I shot over 3500 pictures of the process myself with a wireless remote and put them together to create a stop motion animated film of the entire process.  It can be found on Youtube by searching for the title: Ascension of John Long, or look for my Youtube user name: Mrlongleather, or click on one of my links. 

On October 16th Ascension of John Long will be on display at SOMArt Cultural Center in San Francisco through November 8, 2009.  "Altars for the Spirits/Offerings for the Living: Dia de Los Muertos 2009"

Here's a link to that exhibit:     http://blog.somarts.org/

In October 2009 I completed a new large scale leather mosaic titled: Honoring Four Oakland Heroes.  It is on display at the Meek Estate Mansion in Hayward Ca. from October 10 through November 8, 2009.  It just got the cover of the Oakland Tribune Newspaper along with The Daily Review and The Argus.  I am honored my work is being well received and hope people remember the sacrifice these brave men made to protect the people of Oakland.

Thank you for your time,

Phil Long
